<div id="Modal3" class="modal fade" role="dialog">
  <div class="modal-dialog">

    <!-- Modal content-->
    <div class="modal-content">
 	<div class="modal-body">
        	<div class="container-fluid text-center">
			<h2>Wanderlust</h2><h4>
<img src="wanderlust1.jpg" height=25% width=50%><br><br>She has been bored of all of it lately. The early morning alarms, the same route to work, the company of ‘chivalrous’ men, that bored her even more , the societal pretensions, the tidily mended shelf at the corner of her room, the untouched paperbacks scattered on her bed,  precisely everything. She hated being what she has become. She has been wandering inside her mind lately. That was the safest domicile , she believed. The amorous figures that resided there had proved to be more promising than the real life silhouettes.<br><br>

She sipped from the cup of coffee for the fifth time that day. A strong urge to step into a new terrain began to build inside her. She has always been emotional. No, don’t call her a sentimental fool, for she cares about the feelings more than you do. She feels every single sensation more deeply than you do. She has always been drawn to them. She has wandered off to far off places in her thoughts sitting in her room. She has noticed the rain drops on the  window shield compose themselves into patterns, more than you did. So just don’t 	judge her.<br><br>

<img src="wanderlust2.jpg" height=25% width=50%><br><br>The day seemed to pass at a slow pace. It was warm and pleasant outside. She sat on the veranda floor and watched the busy North  Calcutta  lane below. The tea stall was thronging with people of all ages like ever. The owner of that  ten year old medical store  was engrossed in the Ananda Bazaar Patrika just like every morning. The elders of the area were up for their usual “rock-a-adda” regarding what Modi did and what Mamata needs to do. The same morning blues. How different she has become from these busy chromosomes! She too used to be one of those whose lives were shackled by the “ten to five duty” followed by  irksome bus rides back home. But what about now? All these five days, a nicotine rich diet , ample amount of caffeine and some untimely naps stripped off pleasant dreams persisted.<br><br>

She wanted to leave everything and run away to the mountains. She did not want to be a part of her present life. It was as if she was designed to be there without the will of her soul. She looked for her phone that has been off her sight for more than two days now and she was quite taken aback by the number of missed calls and  messages she had received from her folks. She silently mocked at the  feigning concern of her peer groups. She turned on her data and looked for jobs in Kurseong schools.  A teacher of English required for classes above sixth standard , the ad read for one of the well known schools out there. She instantly jotted down the number. Literature has always been an inexplicable part of her life. It has taught her to love, to feel and most importantly to imagine. She has grown up in the tiny spaces between the vast bookshelves of her father’s study, reading the mystery series of Enid Blyton. The O’Sullivan twins helped her to embrace her hostel life keeping all that homesickness aside. She has been to the countryside where Raju has grown up, through the pages of R.K Narayan’s The Guide. She has wept with Holly after the death of Gerry through the words of Cecelia Ahern. Had she not read The Hungry Tide, she wouldn’t have found Sunderbans so pulchritudinous.<br><br>

It was as if she has lived each and every moment with these characters. Books have helped her to see the sky above her head with a different hue altogether. It was her books that had taught her to accept the different shades of a person. She was grateful to them .<br><br> 

<img src="wanderlust3.jpg" height=25% width=50%><br><br>The online interview was at once executed. Leaving a job of fifty thousand for something that offered only twenty thousand would have been a great deal for a layman but it was just a matter of a few notes missing from her wallet or maybe an abated standard of living. She wasn’t bothered .  She thought about the mornings when she would wake up to see the untimely fog take over the civilization. She thought about the walks on the curved paths, up the hill. She thought about the solitude. The comfortable isolation. The simplicity.

			<br><b><em>Olivia Roy</b></em>
			</h4>
